 issues in Canadian society today. This collection of essays by Canadian scholars explores topics such as Gandhi’s awareness of Canada; the academic study of Gandhi in Canadian higher education; and dimensions of Gandhi’s thought that demand greater attention and have enduring relevance for individuals and communities in Canada. These range from a peace-oriented Islam and participation in direct action campaigns to a more constructive politics and environmental stewardship. This book breaks new ground in the depth of its study of a figure significant for both Canada and the world at large. The themes in this book will be of interest to scholars in Gandhi studies, education, Canadian history, and sociology, as well as to the general reader who seeks to reflect on what traditions of non-violence and conflict resolution championed by Gandhi might contribute to social progress in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNonviolencevCongresses. 0aNonviolence. 0aPassive resistancevCongresses. 0aPassive resistance. 0aStatesmenzIndiavBiographyvCongresses. 0aStatesmenzIndiavBiography. 4aReligion: Eastern Religions. 4aSocial Science: Anthropology. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aCanadian history.  aCanadian politics.  aCanadian universities.  aFirst Nations issues.  aHindu studies.  aIndia.  aIslam and peace.  aaboriginal issues.  adiaspora studies.  aenvironmental protection.  anon-violence.  aphilosophical studies.  apost-secondary education.  areligious studies.  asocial change.  astudy of religion.  aviolence and non-violence.  awho is Gandhi.1 aCoward, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamm, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamm, Alex, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc